<h1>To John Hancock</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Cambridge 7th December 1775</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I wrote you the 4th instant by express to which I beg you will be refferedmy fears that Broughton &amp; Sillman woud not effect any good purpose were too well founded, they are returned, &amp; brought with them three of the principal inhabitants from the Island of St Johns. Mr Collbuck is<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0001" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> president of the
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-03-02-02-pb-0509">[509]</span>
Council, acted as Governor[.] they brought the Governors Commission, the Province Seal &amp;a &amp;a. as the Captains Acted without any Warrant for Such Conduct, I have thought it but justice to discharge these Gentlemen, whose famillys were Left in the utmost distress.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0002" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
<p>I am Credibly informed that James Anderson the Consignee &amp; part owner of the Ship Concord &amp; Cargo, is not only unfreindly to American Liberty, but actualy in arms against us, being Captain of the Scotch Company at Bostonwhether your being acquainted with this Circumstance or not, will operate against the vessell &amp; Cargo, I will not take upon me to Say, but, there are many Articles on board So absolutely necessary, for the Army, that whether She is Made a prize of, or not, we must have them<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0003" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0003-ptr">3</a>I have the honour to be Sir Your most Obedient humble Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Go: Washington</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Signed: a letter not in the authors handwriting, but signed by the author ]">LS</abbr>, in Stephen Moylans writing, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span>, item 152;

<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>;

copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. National Archives and Records Administration, Papers of the Continental Congress, Washington, D.C. ]">DNA:PCC</span> item 169;

copy, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Morristown National Historical Park, Morristown, N.J. [[former abbreviation: NjMoHP]] ]">NjMoHP</span>;

<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.

Congress read this letter on 16 Dec. (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Worthington Chauncey Ford et al., eds. &lt;i&gt;Journals of the Continental Congress, 1774-1789&lt;/i&gt;. 34 vols. Washington, D.C., 190437. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">JCC</span>,</span> 3:432).</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>The letter-book copy and the <abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Handwritten copies in one of the bound volumes used by the team of clerks on GW's headquarters staff who worked from 1781-83 under the direction of Lt. Col. Richard Varick to record correspondence, orders, instructions, and related items from GWs Revolutionary War papers ]">Varick transcript</abbr> read as.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>For the details of this case, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0456" class="document">Phillips Callbeck and Thomas Wright to GW</a>, this date, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0556" class="document">Callbeck to GW, 24 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-03-02-02-0458-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>For the capture of the <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Concord</span> and the question of her legitimacy as a prize, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0431" class="document">Jonathan Glover to GW, 3 Dec.</a>, and <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-03-02-02-0437" class="document">GW to Hancock, 4 Dec. 1775</a>.</p>

</div>
